Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Comparing today's numbers with yesterday's (28 Jul 2020), the global case count rose by 1.7% in the past 24 hours. The USA and Brazil are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts, although India has been rapidly increasing, with daily case counts around 50 000. At the rate of daily reporting, we globally passed the 17 million mark today (29 Jul 2020).

In the past 24 hours, Brazil reported 70 869 cases, followed by USA (69 694) and India (52 249). These 3 countries account for half of all confirmed cases globally (50.7%). There were 6735 deaths reported in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, the Brazil is number one for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by USA, India, South Africa, Colombia, Mexico, Peru, Argentina, Russia, Bangladesh, all known global hotspots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 3009 to 70 869. Other hotspots are seen in the countries numbered 11-20 in this list: Iraq, Iran, Israel, Chile, Philippines, Saudi Arabia, Indonesia, Spain, Kazakhstan and France, and their range of reported new cases is 1392 to 2968.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, there is an increase of 7.8%, and looking at daily reported deaths, the change is decreased by 7.7%.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts and mortality. That being said, the most severely affected region is the Americas with cases increasing on a daily basis, even though the comparative 7-day average suggests things may be slowing down (or reporting is slowing down). - Mod.UBA]
